The paper discusses a framework for planning in domains with continuous actions and non-linear constraints, which is relevant to several sub-fields of computer science. The use of blackbox generators and infinite streams of objects suggests a focus on artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and robotics (cs.RO). The extension of the STRIPS language and the algorithms for reducing problems to finite-domain planning problems suggest a focus on planning (cs.PL). The use of machine learning techniques to handle complex constraints suggests a focus on machine learning (cs.LG). Finally, the application of the framework to a high-dimensional, continuous robotic task and motion planning domain suggests a focus on systems and control (cs.SY).
